@subsection Associative Arrays

APL arrays are primarily indexed with numbers (or arrays of numbers), which is
also the most efficient method. Many other languages provide, in either addition
or else alternatively, a method to index arrays by @b{keys}, where the keys
are frequently characters strings. Such arrays are commonly referred to
as @b{associative arrays}.

APL has no associative array per se, but the structured variables in GNU APL
can be used for the same purpose. The only limitation is (currently) that the
keys need to be character strings (as opposed to arbitrary APL values).

That is, in GNU APL an associative array

@itemize
@item is a structured variable, and
@item can be indexed with arbitrary (!) strings
@end itemize

As long as the strings that are used as keys follow the same rules as APL
variable names (no leading digit, no '.' etc.), a structured variable can
also be indexed with a string. That can be useful if keys are being computed
or passed as function arguments. However, unlike indexing of APL arrays with
numbers, only one key per (bracket-) index is permitted.

@verbatim
   A.key вҶҗ 42
   A.key
42
   A['key']
42
   A['key']вҶҗ24
   A.key
24
   A['key' 'key']   вҚқ not allowed even though 'key' is a valid member
DOMAIN ERROR
      D['key' 'key']

@end verbatim

Strings that do not follow the rules for variable names can be used with bracket
index, but not with the .member syntax:

@verbatim
      ASSOC вҶҗ 38 вҺ•CR 8
      KEYвҶҗ'key.dot'   вҚқ works, but avoid such keys
      ASSOC[KEY]вҶҗ42
      ASSOC[KEY]
42
      ASSOC[KEY]вҶҗ43
      ASSOC[KEY]
43
      ASSOC.key.dot   вҚқ won't work: 'key.dot' is a single key, but key.dot is 2 keys
VALUE ERROR+
      ASSOC.key.dot
               ^
      )MORE
member access: structure ASSOC has no member key

      ASSOC.key.dotвҶҗ44   вҚқ works: 2 (nested) keys
      ASSOC.key.dot
44
      ASSOC['key.dot']   вҚқ works: one key containing '.'
43
@end verbatim

This is because ASSOC.key.dot above is being tokenized by the APL parser into
[ASSOC] [key] [dot], while 'key.dot' is a single key. The example above (with
different values for ASSOC.key.dot and for ASSOC['key.dot'] demonstrates why
such keys are better avoided.

Even though (one) bracket index can only access the top-level members of a
structured variable, repeated bracket index (or dyadic PICK) can be used to
access deeper nesting levels:

@verbatim
      D.b.cвҶҗ42
      D['b.c']   вҚқ will fail
INDEX ERROR+
      D['b.c']
      ^^
      )MORE
member access: member b.c was not found. The valid members are:
      b

      D['b']['c']   вҚқ will work
42

      вҚқ alternatively: use PICK
      вҚқ
      'b' 'c' вҠғ D   вҚқ fails: 'b' 'c' is 'ab'
      "b" "c" вҠғ D   вҚқ works
42

@end verbatim

In the above examples each bracket index (or each element of PICK) discards the
current top-level structure and descends into the structured sub-variable of
the chosen member. In this case PICK is more efficient since repeated bracket
index creates copies of the intermediate structured sub-variables.

If a variable is used as a structured variable then the number of its members
is typically small (since every member name occurs explicitly in the APL code
that uses it). If a variable is used as an associative array, then the member
names are typically being computed and the number of members can become rather
large (like the different key values in a database). When such a variable
(i.e. with many members) reaches its capacity, then finding a member (when
the array is indexed), or finding an unused place in the variable (when a new
member is added) becomes slower and slower. The GNU APL implementation has
addressed this by hashing into the variable (based on the member name)
instead of, for example, sequentially allocating the members. This is very
fast under normal circumstances, but becomes as slow as sequential allocation
when the number of members in the variable reaches its current capacity.
For this reason, if a structured variable is used as an associative array,
e.g. as a database, then it is better to not rely on the (automatic)
reorganization of the variable, but to create the variable with a large
enough (with 38 вҺ•CR) from the beginning.

If that is not possible (because the (performance-) problem has occurred after
the variable was created, then one can manually increase the capacity like this:

@verbatim
      TMP вҶҗ 39 вҺ•CR ASSOC_ARRAY   вҚқ save ASSOC_ARRAY as normal APL array
      вҠЈ вҺ•EX 'ASSOC_ARRAY'        вҚқ erase it so that it can be assigned
      ASSOC_ARRAY вҶҗ 38 вҺ•CR TMP   вҚқ new associative array with вүҘ twice the size
@end verbatim

As a rule of thumb, associative arrays will be fast as long their capacity is
more than twice the number of their members. The expression ASSOC_ARRAY[;1]
returns all keys (= members) of ASSOC_ARRAY, therefore the number of members
is вҚҙASSOC_ARRAY[;1] and the capacity is вҶ‘вҚҙASSOC_ARRAY.


@node    Section 2.17
@section Monadic вҠў and вҠЈ, dyadic вҠў with Axis

Monadic вҠў is the identity function. It returns its (committed or non-committed)
right argument as a non-committed value.

Conversely, monadic вҠЈ (called @b{Hide} in GNU APL) discards its (committed or
non-committed) right argument and returns a committed integer scalar 0. 

For the most part there is no difference between a committed value (= a value
that was assigned to a variable, including вҺ• and вҚһ) and a non-committed value.
The point where it does make a difference is when the value the final result
of a statement (as opposed to an intermediate result inside a statement). In
that situation (and only there) a non-committed value is being printed while
a committed value is not.

You can use вҠў is a similar fashion as вҺ•вҶҗ at the left end of a statement,
in order to print a value even though it was previously assigned to a
variable.

The main motivation for вҠЈ is that, at least in GNU APL, lambdas always return
a value. However, if a lambda is used only for the sake of its side effects, say
to print something, then the value returned by the lambda is often of no
interest and only messes up the APL output. In that situation вҠЈ can be used
to suppress the printing of undesired return values from lambdas.

In earlier GNU APL versions, вҠЈB and вҠўB would both return B; with вҠЈ as committed
value and with вҠў as non-committed value. But since the only real-life purpose
of вҠЈ is to suppress the printing of B, the implementation of вҠЈ was changed to
returning an committed integer scalar 0 instead of committed B. That reduced
the run-time of вҠЈB from O(,B) to O(1). Also, вҠўB is marginally faster than вҺ•вҶҗB.

Dyadic вҠў with axis is a selection function that generalizes вҠЈ and вҠў.

Let @b{ZвҶҗA вҠЈ[X] B}. Then:

@itemize
@item if X is a one-element vector and вҶ‘X is 0 then Z вүЎ A,
@item if X is a one-element vector and вҶ‘X is 1 then Z вүЎ B,
@item otherwise X selects corresponding items of A resp. B if the correspondent
 elements of X are 0 or 1 respectively. In that case, the shapes of A and B
 must match the shape of X, but one-element A or B are scalar extended to the
 shape of X.
@end itemize

Example:
@verbatim

      AвҶҗ2 3вҚҙ'abcdef'
      BвҶҗ2 3вҚҙвҚі6
      XвҶҗ2 3вҚҙ0 1 0 1 0 1
      A вҠў[X] B
a 2 c
4 e 6

   A вҠў[X] '*'
a*c
*e*

  '*' вҠў[X] B
* 2 *
4 * 6

@end verbatim


@node    Section 2.18
@section Bit-wise Logical Functions вҠӨвҲ§, вҠӨвҲЁ, вҠӨвҚІ, вҠӨвҚұ, Tвү , and T=

The APL functions And (вҲ§), Or (вҲЁ), Nand (вҚІ), and Nor (вҚұ) operate primarily on
Boolean integers. Primarily means that the the LCM variant for вҲ§
and the GCD variant for вҲЁ are not considered in this context. (The LCM and
GCD variants are defined in the ISO standard and supported in GNU APL but
not in IBM APL2).

However, probably more often than not one needs to compute Boolean functions
between the bits of arbitrary (non-Boolean) integers and not between entire
Boolean integers 0 or 1. Although that is possible to do in standard APL,
the procedure is fairly awkward and, more importantly, inefficient:

@itemize
@item
convert every integer argument X to a 64-item Boolean vector XвҶҗ(64вҚҙ2)вҠӨX,
@item
call the Boolean function вҲ§, вҲЁ, вҚІ, вҚұ, =, or вү  with the converted arguments,
and
@item
convert the Boolean result vector R back to the integer result ZвҶҗ2вҠҘR
@end itemize

Note: for Boolean arguments the APL functions вү  resp. = can be used to compute
the more customary Boolean functions XOR and XNOR. In this context = and вү  are
treated as Boolean functions even though they accept non-Boolean arguments,

For example (using  5 вҺ•CR (4вҚҙ256)вҠӨX to display X in hex):

@verbatim
      5 вҺ•CR (4вҚҙ256)вҠӨ   AвҶҗ$ABBADEAD
ABBADEAD
      5 вҺ•CR (4вҚҙ256)вҠӨ   BвҶҗ$00FF00FF
00FF00FF

      5 вҺ•CR (4вҚҙ256)вҠӨ   2вҠҘ ((64вҚҙ2)вҠӨA) вҲ§ (64вҚҙ2)вҠӨB
00BA00AD

@end verbatim

With the bit-wise @b{And} (вҲЈвҲ§) the same can be achieved in a simpler fashion
and far more efficiently:

@verbatim
      вҚқ Traditional AND
      5 вҺ•CR (4вҚҙ256)вҠӨ   AвҶҗ$ABBADEAD
ABBADEAD
      5 вҺ•CR (4вҚҙ256)вҠӨ   BвҶҗ$00FF00FF
00FF00FF

      вҚқ bit-wise AND
      5 вҺ•CR (4вҚҙ256)вҠӨ   A вҠӨвҲ§ B
00BA00AD
@end verbatim

@subsection Dyadic вҠӨвҲ§, вҠӨвҲЁ, вҠӨвҚІ, вҠӨвҚұ, вҠӨ=, and вҠӨвү 

The dyadic forms of @b{вҠӨвҲ§}, @b{вҠӨвҲЁ}, @b{вҠӨвҚІ}, and @b{вҠӨвҚұ} are simply the bit-wise
variants of their Boolean counterparts:

@verbatim
      A вҠӨвҲ§ B    вҶҗвҶ’    2вҠҘ ((64вҚҙ2)вҠӨA) вҲ§ (64вҚҙ2)вҠӨB      вҚқ aka. AND
      A вҠӨвҲЁ B    вҶҗвҶ’    2вҠҘ ((64вҚҙ2)вҠӨA) вҲЁ (64вҚҙ2)вҠӨB      вҚқ aka. OR
      A вҠӨвҚІ B    вҶҗвҶ’    2вҠҘ ((64вҚҙ2)вҠӨA) вҚІ (64вҚҙ2)вҠӨB      вҚқ aka. NAND
      A вҠӨвҚұ B    вҶҗвҶ’    2вҠҘ ((64вҚҙ2)вҠӨA) вҚұ (64вҚҙ2)вҠӨB      вҚқ aka. NOR
      A вҠӨвү  B    вҶҗвҶ’    2вҠҘ ((64вҚҙ2)вҠӨA) вү  (64вҚҙ2)вҠӨB      вҚқ aka. XOR
      A вҠӨ= B    вҶҗвҶ’    2вҠҘ ((64вҚҙ2)вҠӨA) = (64вҚҙ2)вҠӨB      вҚқ aka. NXOR or XNOR
@end verbatim

@subsection Monadic вҠӨвҲЁ and вҠӨвҚұ

@b{вҠӨвҲ§} and @b{вҠӨвҚІ} do not have a monadic form, but @b{вҠӨвҲ§}, @b{вҠӨвҲЁ}, and @b{вҠӨвҚұ} do.
Formally monadic @b{вҠӨвҲЁ} resp, @b{вҠӨвҚұ} are dyadic @b{вҠӨвҲЁ} resp, @b{вҠӨвҚұ} with
a left argument of 0:

@verbatim
      вҠӨвҲЁ B    вҶҗвҶ’    0 вҠӨвҲЁ B      вҚқ real B to nearby integer
      вҠӨвҚұ B    вҶҗвҶ’    0 вҠӨвҚұ B      вҚқ bit-wise Not
@end verbatim

Even though Or-ing a Boolean vector with 0 itself has no effect, the
monadic вҠӨвҲЁ and вҠӨвҚұ are still useful due to their side effects: conversion
from near-integer float values to integers (monadic @b{вҠӨвҲЁ} and inversion
of the bits (monadic @b{вҠӨвҚұ}, The latter is needed since вҲј has a monadic
form and as a consequence вҠӨвҲј was not an option for a bit-wise @b{Not}
function.

Monadic @b{вҠӨвҚұ B} is the bit-wise @b{Not} function of its argument:

      вҠӨвҚұ B    вҶҗвҶ’    2вҠҘ ~(64вҚҙ2)вҠӨB

Monadic @b{вҠӨвҲЁ B} converts near-integer values B into true integers:

@verbatim
      26 вҺ•CR    1            вҚқ integer
16
      26 вҺ•CR    1.1          вҚқ real
32
      26 вҺ•CR    1Г·1          вҚқ integer
16
      26 вҺ•CR    1.1Г·1.1      вҚқ real
32
      26 вҺ•CR    вҠӨвҲЁ 1.1Г·1.1   вҚқ integer
16
@end verbatim

That also works for complex numbers with a near-zero imaginary part:

@verbatim
      26 вҺ•CR    1.1J0Г·1.1      вҚқ real
32
      26 вҺ•CR    вҠӨвҲЁ 1.1J0Г·1.1      вҚқ integer
16
@end verbatim

As a matter of fact, @b{вҠӨвҲЁ} works for all near-Gaussian complex numbers,
but the effect is not visible with 26 вҺ•CR since Gaussian and non-Gaussian
complex numbers have the same cell type in GNU APL.

@subsection Monadic вҠӨвҲ§

The ISO standard defines two different concepts to decide if a real number R
is close to an integer I,
@itemize
@item
the real number R is said to be @b{near} to integer I if the absolute
value of I-R is smaller than some small constant called the @b{integer
tolerance} in ISO and @b{system tolerance} in IBM APL2. The @b{integer
tolerance} is typically platform dependent (1EВҜ10 in GNU APL).

@item
the real number R is said to be @b{equal to integer I within вҺ•CT} if the
absolute value of (I-R)/I is smaller than вҺ•CT.
@end itemize

The first concept is an absolute distance from a real R to a nearby integer I
while the second concept is a relative distance (larger numbers are allowed to
be farther away from a nearby integer than smaller numbers). The two concepts
differ in the same way that absolute and relative errors do.

Now, all bit-wise functions described so far use the first concept, i,e,
if their their arguments are real or complex, then the smallest distance to
a (nearby) integer must not exceed the @b{integer tolerance}. In some contexts
that could be difficult to achieve and for that reason GNU APL provides
monadic вҠӨвҲ§ which works like вҠӨвҲЁ except that the permitted distance from a
nearby integer is now controlled by вҺ•CT rather than by the integer tolerance.

All bit-wise logical functions throw a DOMAIN ERROR if an argument is not close
enough to an integer. integer tolerance is typically smaller than вҺ•CT and
in that case is вҠӨвҲ§ little more tolerant than вҠӨвҲЁ regarding the distance to
nearby integers. In addition вҠӨвҲ§ gives the user (via вҺ•CT) more control over
the permitted tolerance for real numbers in the neighborhood of integers.

@subsection Character Arguments for Monadic вҠӨвҚұ and Dyadic вҠӨвҲ§, вҠӨвҲЁ, ==, and вү вү 

Some of the bit-wise operations are allowed to have characters as their right
argument. If the right argument is a character then the result is a character
as well. This can be useful for masking purposes such as extracting the lower
7 bits of 8-bit bytes containing ASCII characters.

The characters involved are treated as 32 bit quantities:

@verbatim
      5 вҺ•CR 'A'
41
      5 вҺ•CR вҠӨвҚұ'A'                       вҚқ Note that 5 вҺ•CR ANDs with $FF
BE

      256 256 256 256вҠӨ вҺ•UCS вҠӨвҚұ 'A'      вҚқ вҠӨвҚұ 'A' is FFFFFFBE
255 255 255 190
      256 256 256 256вҠӨ$FFFFFFBE
255 255 255 190
@end verbatim

@node    Section 2.19
@section Generalized вҚі

@subsection Generalized monadic вҚі

The standard function @b{Interval} (ZвҶҗвҚіB) requires its argument B to be a
scalar or a length 1 vector. The result ZвҶҗвҚіB then contains all possible
indices of values which have shape B.

Generalized monadic вҚі extends this concept to integer vectors B with more
than 1 element. The result ZвҶҗвҚіB again contains all possible indices of a
value which has shape B, but the rank of B can now be more than 1. The items
of Z are nested integer vectors as opposed to integer scalars in the standard
case.

@subsection Generalized dyadic вҚі

The standard function @b{Index Of} (ZвҶҗAвҚіB) requires its left argument A to be
a scalar or a vector of rank 1. The items of the result Z are the (first)
positions (= indices) of the corresponding items of B in A (for the items found
in A) or else вҺ•IO+вҚҙA (which is an invalid index of A) for the items of B that
are not found in A.

Generalized dyadic вҚі extends this concept to find the (first) indices of the
corresponding items of B in A (in ravel order) where the rank of A is > 1.
Each item of the result Z is then either a nested integer vector (if the item
was found) or @b{- different from the standard case (!) -} the empty vector вҚ¬
if the item was not found).

@node    Section 2.20
@section вҢ№[X] - QR Factorization

ZвҶҗвҢ№[X] B computes a QR factorization of the real or complex matrix B. The axis
argument X is used to clear near-0 matrix items to exactly 0.0 during the
computation. Set XвҶҗвҺ•CT if unsure.

The result Z is a triple (QT R Ri)вҶҗZ with the following properties.
Let вҚҙB=(M, N).

* QT is an orthogonal MГ—M matrix, i.e QT@sup{-1} = QT@sup{T}, resp. QT +.Г— вҚүQT
 is the MГ—M identity matrix I@sub{M} (with I@sub{M}вҶҗвҲҳ.=вҚЁвҚіM).

* R is an upper triangular MГ—N matrix, i.e. R[m;n] = 0 for n < m, and

* Ri is the inverse of R, i.e. Ri +.Г— R is the identity matrix I@sub{N}.

* (вҚүQT) +.Г— R = B.

Note that, unlike in standard QR factorizations, the matrix QT returned by
вҢ№[X] is already inverted (i.e. transposed since QT is orthogonal). The
reason is that the algorithm used can transpose Q with no extra cost and
usually the first step after a QR factorization is to transpose the
returned Q matrix. This first transpose step is therefore not needed.

Example 1 (real B)
@verbatim

      вҺ•вҶҗBвҶҗ3 3вҚҙ 1 1 3 2 4 2 4 8 7
1 1 3
2 4 2
4 8 7

      (QT R Ri)вҶҗвҢ№[вҺ•CT]B
      QвҶҗвҚүQT   вҚқ recover the non-transposed Q

      4 вҺ•CR 0 4вҚ• Q
