A new feature of вҺ•FIO (which is not available with the native function FILE_IO)
is вҺ•FIO[49]. вҺ•FIO[49] is a monadic operator which takes a monadic conversion
function as function argument. For example:

@smallexample
ZвҶҗF вҺ•FIO[49] 'filename'
@end smallexample

reads the file named filename line by line. For every line read, the conversion
function F is called and the result returned by F is enclosed and stored in Z.
In other words,

@smallexample
ZвҶҗF вҺ•FIO[49] 'filename'
@end smallexample

does:

@smallexample
Z FВЁZвҶҗвҺ•FIO[49] 'filename'
@end smallexample


@node    Section 2.27
@section вҺ•FFT - Fast Fourier Transform

For those interested in signal processing and the like, GNU APL provides вҺ•FFT:

The monadic form вҺ•FFT B is a shortcut for the dyadic form 0 вҺ•FFT B. It computes
the FFT of complex or real B without applying a window function.

The dyadic form A вҺ•FFT B provides more control over what вҺ•FFT computes. A is
an integer scalar which falls into one of three ranges.

The first range from ВҜ15 to ВҜ10 does not compute an FFT, but returns the result
of multiplying B with one of several window functions, that are frequently
used in the context of FFTs. The result has same shape as B and can be used for
analyzing or troubleshooting FFTs:

@itemize
@item A=ВҜ10: no FFT, return the Hann window applied to B
@item A=ВҜ11: no FFT, return the Hamming window applied to B
@item A=ВҜ12: no FFT, return the Blackman window applied to B
@item A=ВҜ13: no FFT, return the Blackman-Harris window applied to B
@item A=ВҜ14: no FFT, return the Blackman-Nuttal window applied to B
@item A=ВҜ15: no FFT, return the Flat-Top window applied to B
@end itemize

The second range around 0 contains the computation of the forward and inverse
FFTs:

@itemize
@item  0 вҺ•FFT B returns the "normal" (aka. forward) FFT of the numeric array B.
@item ВҜ1 вҺ•FFT B returns the inverse FFT of the numeric array B.
@end itemize

The third range from 10 to 15 corresponds to the first range and first
multiplies B with a window function and then computes the FFT:

@itemize
@item A=10: FFT(B Г— Hann window)
@item A=11: FFT(B Г— Hamming window)
@item A=12: FFT(B Г— Blackman window)
@item A=13: FFT(B Г— Blackman-Harris window)
@item A=14: FFT(B Г— Blackman-Nuttal window)
@item A=15: FFT(B Г— Flat-Top window)
@end itemize

вҚҙвҚҙB can be 1 (one-dimensional FFT, the most common case) or more. The
implementation of вҺ•FFT uses libfftw3, aka. "The fastest Fourier Transform in
the West". GNU APL checks the presence of libfftw3 when it is ./configure'd.
If libfftw3 is present then вҺ•FFT will hopefully return the expected result;
if not then a DOMAIN ERROR will be raised when вҺ•FFT is being used.

вҺ•FFT honors the presence of /etc/fftw/wisdom (see man fftw-wisdom) to speed
up the computations performed by вҺ•FFT. Creating /etc/fftw/wisdom will take a
few hours, though, so that creating it will not pay off for most mortals.

@node    Section 2.28
@section вҺ•GTK - GTK Interface

GTK (Gimp ToolKit) is a rather powerful library for creating graphical user
interfaces (GUIs). вҺ•GTK makes a subset of the almost 10000 functions in the
different GTK libraries available to GNU APL programs. With вҺ•GTK a GNU APL
program can, for example, replace the somewhat crude вҺ• or вҚһ input methods
of standard APL with a more intuitive GUI.

The details of using вҺ•GTK would go far beyond the scope of this info manual
and has therefore been put into a separate document.
See: @b{HOWTOs/Quad-GTK.html}.

@c ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
@node    Section 2.29
@section вҺ•JSON - JSON Parsing

GNU APL provides вҺ•JSON for decoding and encoding JSON strings and files.
A (valid) JSON string is mapped to an APL value as follows:

@itemize
@item JSON value вҶҗвҶ’ structured or non-structured APL value
@item JSON number вҶҗвҶ’  APL number
@item JSON string вҶҗвҶ’  APL string
@item JSON literal вҶҗвҶ’  enclosed APL string (one of either вҠӮ'null', вҠӮ'true',
      or вҠӮ'false' )
@item JSON array вҶҗвҶ’  APL vector
@item JSON object вҶҗвҶ’  structured APL value (associative array)
@end itemize

@subsection Monadic  вҺ•JSON

ZвҶҗвҺ•JSON B converts the string B into an APL value according to the mapping
above. If that fails then command )MORE provides information about the error
and where in B the error was detected.

@subsection Dyadic  вҺ•JSON

ZвҶҗA вҺ•JSON B performs one of the following conversions:

@itemize
@item @b{ZвҶҗ0 вҺ•JSON B} is the same as monadic ZвҶҗвҺ•JSON B.

@item @b{ZвҶҗ1 вҺ•JSON B} is like ZвҶҗ0 вҺ•XML B, except that B is not the JSON
string itself but the name of a file from which an JSON string
is read.

@item @b{ZвҶҗ2 вҺ•JSON B} is the inverse of ZвҶҗ0 вҺ•XML B. It converts an APL
value to a JSON string.

@item @b{ZвҶҗ3 вҺ•JSON B} is like 2 вҺ•JSON B, except that the member names
(keys) of all JSON objects are sorted alphabetically. That is of little use
(but costs perfomance) if Z is not displayed but processed further, but
it could help troubleshooting when Z is displayed and the number of keys in Z
is large.
@end itemize

@node    Section 2.30
@section вҺ•MAP  - Map Value

вҺ•MAP changes the ravel items of its right argument according to a mapping
table provided as its left argument. Let ZвҶҗA вҺ•MAP B.

The left argument A of ZвҶҗA вҺ•MAP B shall be a NГ—2 matrix. Each 2-element row of
A, say A[J;], specifies a separate mapping A[J;1] вҶ’ A[J;2]. The result Z has
the same shape as the right argument B. The items Z[...] iof ther result are
constructed from their corresponding items B[...] in B as follows:

@itemize

@item if B[...] вүЎ A[J;1] for some J then Z[...] is A[J;2].

@item otherwise B[...] is different from all A[1;J] and then Z[...] is B[...]

@end itemize

In other words, Z is B, but with items of B found in A[;1] replaced by their
mapped item A[;2].

In practice th left argument A is frequently created from a literal APL value
such as 5 2вҚҙ'eEwWaAzZ92' in the example below. To simplify these cases, A вҺ•MAP B
also accepts a vector instead of a NГ—2 matrix:

      A вҺ•MAP B   вҶҗвҶ’   ((N 2)вҚҙA) вҺ•MAP B   if (2Г—N)   вҶҗвҶ’    вҚҙA


Examples:

@verbatim
      вҚқ the map A
      вҠўAвҶҗ5 2вҚҙ'eEwWaAzZ92'
eE    вҚқ map 'e' вҶ’ 'E'
wW    вҚқ map 'w' вҶ’ 'W'
aA    вҚқ map 'a' вҶ’ 'A'
zZ    вҚқ map 'z' вҶ’ 'Z'
92    вҚқ map '9' вҶ’ '2'

      вҚқ the value B being mapped
      вҠўBвҶҗ'Halloween'
Halloween

      вҚқ the result of A вҺ•MAP B
      A вҺ•MAP B
HAlloWEEn

      AвҶҗ'eEwWaAzZ92'   вҚқ vector A instead of NГ—2 matrix
      A вҺ•MAP B
HAlloWEEn

@end verbatim

NOTES:
@itemize @bullet
@item
The keys of the mapping A (i.e. the elements in column A[;1]) must be
unique. If they are not then the mapping is ambiguous and a DOMAIN ERROR
is raised.

@item
Nested items in B: if an item of B is nested, then it is either equal to some
(also nested) key, say A[N;1], (in that case it is being mapped to A[N;2] in
the result), or it is different from all keys in A[;1] (and in that case the
corresponding item in the result is the item in B.

@item
Nested items in A: if a key, say A[N;1], is nested and matches an equal (hence
also nested) item in B, then the corresponding item in the result will be
A[N;2] (which may or may not be nested). If a (nested or not nested) key A[N;1]
is equal to an item in B, then the corresponding item in the result will be
nested iff A[N;2] is nested. If, for some N, the depths of A[N;1] and A[N;2]
differ, then then depths of B and A вҺ•MAP B may differ as well. That is, вҺ•MAP
conserves the shape of B, but not necessarily the depth of B.

@item

By default the mapping of B is non-recursive, i.e. the top-level items of
B are compared with the top-level keys A[;1], and nested keys and items of B
are handled as described above.

Sometrimes, however, it is desirable to recursively descend into the nested
sub-values of B (though never of A). This can be achieved by enclosing A as
shown in the examples below.
@end itemize

@verbatim
      AвҶҗ5 2вҚҙ'eEwWaAzZ92'
      BвҶҗ'Hal' 'low' 'een'   вҚқ nested B
      4 вҺ•CR A вҺ•MAP B        вҚқ non-recursive (none of the keys in A[;1] matches)
в”ҸвҶ’в”Ғв”Ғв”Ғв”Ғв”Ғв”Ғв”Ғв”Ғв”Ғв”Ғв”Ғв”Ғв”Ғв”Ғв”Ғв”Ғв”“
в”ғв”ҸвҶ’в”Ғв”Ғв”“ в”ҸвҶ’в”Ғв”Ғв”“ в”ҸвҶ’в”Ғв”Ғв”“в”ғ
в”ғв”ғHalв”ғ в”ғlowв”ғ в”ғeenв”ғв”ғ
в”ғв”—в”Ғв”Ғв”Ғв”ӣ в”—в”Ғв”Ғв”Ғв”ӣ в”—в”Ғв”Ғв”Ғв”ӣв”ғ
в”—вҲҠв”Ғв”Ғв”Ғв”Ғв”Ғв”Ғв”Ғв”Ғв”Ғв”Ғв”Ғв”Ғв”Ғв”Ғв”Ғв”Ғв”ӣ

      4 вҺ•CR (вҠӮA) вҺ•MAP B   вҚқ recursive (some simple keys in A[;1] match)
в”ҸвҶ’в”Ғв”Ғв”Ғв”Ғв”Ғв”Ғв”Ғв”Ғв”Ғв”Ғв”Ғв”Ғв”Ғв”Ғв”Ғв”Ғв”“
в”ғв”ҸвҶ’в”Ғв”Ғв”“ в”ҸвҶ’в”Ғв”Ғв”“ в”ҸвҶ’в”Ғв”Ғв”“в”ғ
в”ғв”ғHAlв”ғ в”ғloWв”ғ в”ғEEnв”ғв”ғ
в”ғв”—в”Ғв”Ғв”Ғв”ӣ в”—в”Ғв”Ғв”Ғв”ӣ в”—в”Ғв”Ғв”Ғв”ӣв”ғ
в”—вҲҠв”Ғв”Ғв”Ғв”Ғв”Ғв”Ғв”Ғв”Ғв”Ғв”Ғв”Ғв”Ғв”Ғв”Ғв”Ғв”Ғв”ӣ


@end verbatim

@node    Section 2.31
@section вҺ•PLOT - Plot Data

вҺ•PLOT is a function for visualizing numerical APL values. The values to be
plotted are provided as the right argument of вҺ•PLOT while the optional
left argument controls details of the output, such as the plot window size,
colors for plot lines, points, and grids, etc.

The general syntax of вҺ•PLOT is:

@verbatim
   вҺ•PLOT ''      вҚқ show a list of attributes and their default values
   HвҶҗвҺ•PLOT B     вҚқ plot B with all attributes set to their default values
   HвҶҗA вҺ•PLOT B   вҚқ plot B with some of the default attributes overridden
   вҺ•PLOT H       вҚқ close the plot window with handle H
   вҺ•PLOT  0      вҚқ verbosity: OFF (no debug output)
   вҺ•PLOT ВҜ1      вҚқ verbosity: ON (print attribute values before plotting)
   вҺ•PLOT ВҜ2      вҚқ verbosity: DEBUG (also print debug information)
   вҺ•PLOT ВҜ3      вҚқ close all plot windows
   вҺ•PLOT ВҜ6      вҚқ return all open plot window handles H
@end verbatim

@subsection The Plot Data B

The plot data @b{B} can be a vector (for a single plot line to be drawn)
or a matrix (in that case one plot line per matrix row is being
drawn, by default in different colors). Each data item has to be numeric
and represents one point in the plot. The points that are adjacent in a row
of the matrix are connected by lines. By default plotted points are black and
the lines connecting them are green (for the first plot line). However, all
colors used, all diameters of points, and all thicknesses of the lines can
be fine-tuned by overriding the default values (see dyadic A вҺ•PLOT B below).

@subsubsection Complex Plot Data B

If a data item B[N] or B[row;N] is @b{complex}, say B[N] = x + iy. then it is
placed (after some scaling) at position (x, y) of the plot. The X-range
[Xmin ... Xmax] of the plot is then determined by the real parts of B,
and the Y-range [Ymin ... Ymax] of the plot is determined by the imaginary
parts of B. That is:

@verbatim
Xmin вҶҗ вҢҠ/,9в—ӢB    вҚқ smallest real part of B
Xmax вҶҗ вҢҲ/,9в—ӢB    вҚқ largest real part of B
Ymin вҶҗ вҢҠ/,11в—ӢB   вҚқ smallest imaginary part of B
Ymax вҶҗ вҢҲ/,11в—ӢB   вҚқ largest imaginary part of B
@end verbatim

Example (plot a circle (actually: a regular 20-gon)):

@verbatim
      вҺ•PLOT +вҢҝ1 0J1Г—[1]1 2 вҲҳ.в—Ӣ (0,вҚі2Г—N) Г— в—ӢГ·NвҶҗ10
@end verbatim

produces this plot window (only visible in the HTML version of this document;
in text mode see file @b{doc/PLOT_circle.png}):

@image{PLOT_circle}

@subsubsection Real Plot Data B

On the other hand, if a data item B[N] or B[row;N] is @b{real}, then it is
placed at position (N, x) of the plot. The X-range is then
[вҺ•IO ... вҺ•IO + ВҜ1вҶ‘вҚҙB] and the Y-range [Y@sub{min} ... Y@sub{max}] of the
plot is determined by the values parts of B. That is:

@verbatim
Xmin вҶҗ вҺ•IO             вҚқ smallest real part of B
Xmax вҶҗ ВҜ1 + вҺ•IO + вҚҙB   вҚқ largest real part of B
Ymin вҶҗ вҢҠ/,B            вҚқ smallest value in B
Ymax вҶҗ вҢҲ/,B            вҚқ largest value in B
@end verbatim

Example:

@verbatim
      вҺ•PLOT 0 1 ВҜ1 2 ВҜ2 3 ВҜ3
@end verbatim

produces this plot window (only visible in the HTML version of this document;
in text mode see file @b{doc/PLOT_zigzag.png}):

@image{PLOT_zigzag}

NOTE: In theory one can also mix real and complex values, even though doing so
makes little sense. If at least one item of the plot data B is complex, then
all real items in B are taken as complex with imaginary part 0.

@subsection The Plot Attributes A

There are a number of attributes like colors, point sizes, line widths,
etc. that control how the resulting plot will look like.

Similar to вҺ•CR and вҺ•FIO, an empty argument B in вҺ•PLOT B displays a list of
the arguments. The list of arguments grows over time and therefore the list
displayed by вҺ•PLOT '' may be more up-to-date than this description.
For example:

